TEST DESCRIPTION DOCUMENT
Socket Programming Assignment 1

Test Description Document
Author: Aa’dil Khamis Ngangila

1. Objective of Testing

The objective of testing was to verify:

Correct message transmission

Correct integer parsing

Proper sum calculation

Correct server shutdown behavior

Proper socket closing

2. Test Cases Performed
Test Case 1 — Normal Input

Input:

25

Server number: 50
Expected sum: 75

Result:

Server displayed correct values

Client displayed correct values

Sum matched on both sides

Status: ✅ Passed

Test Case 2 — Lower Boundary

Input:

1

Expected sum: 51

Result:
Correct output.

Status: ✅ Passed

Test Case 3 — Upper Boundary

Input:

100

Expected sum: 150

Result:
Correct output.

Status: ✅ Passed

Test Case 4 — Invalid Input (Above Range)

Input:

150

Expected behavior:

Server detects invalid number

Server terminates

Sockets close properly

Result:
Server shut down as expected.

Status: ✅ Passed

Test Case 5 — Multiple Sequential Clients

Procedure:

Run client multiple times sequentially.

Result:
Server handled connections correctly.

Status: ✅ Passed

3. Verification of Correctness

For each valid test:

Sum computed on server matched sum computed on client.

No data corruption observed.

No socket leakage occurred.

Connections were properly closed.

4. Known Limitations

The following limitations were identified:

Server is not concurrent.

No handling for malformed messages.

No timeout mechanism.

Client does not validate input before sending.

No encryption.

5. Conclusion

All functional requirements were tested and verified. The program behaves correctly under normal and boundary conditions and properly handles invalid input as specified.